<h2 style="text-align: center">URBAN - RURAL DIVIDE</h2>

<p>India's rural hinterland [a region remote from urban areas] is catching up with urban areas in the use of electricity as the main source of lighting, in access to banking facilities and tap water for drinking, bridging the old rural-urban divide.
<p>The housing, households' amenities and assets census for 2011 once again showed that rural India is fast converting into a more urbanized society.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.adbi.org/e-newsline/120316.html)

<p><b>Urbanization: -</b> Urbanization is a process in which people migrate to urban areas from rural areas. It includes the physical growth of urban societies.

\image image1
<br>Fig. 1. Urbanizaion
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.newworldencyclopedia.org/entry/Urbanization)

<p><b>Urbanization in India: -</b> 
<p>Urbanization in India was mainly caused after independence, due to adoption of mixed system of economy by the country which gave rise to the development of private sector.
<p>Indian cities have witnessed highest growth for any urban cluster in the world, with Delhi and Mumbai topping the list. India's population rose to 1.21 billion in 2011 in a decade with 35% of them living in cities, meaning fastest urbanization in the past five decades.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urbanisation_in_India)
<br>(http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/World-s-fastest-urbanization-is-in-India/Article1-700245.aspx)

<p><b>Factors affecting urbanization: -</b> 
<p>Urbanization occurs because towns and cities have: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">(1)  more jobs / services
<br>(2) better transport / communication
<br>(3) better nightlife
<br>(4) better education facilities
<br>(5) more access to health-care
<p style="text-align: right">(http://wiki.answers.com/Q/What_are_the_factors_affecting_urbanization)

<p><b>Impacts of urbanization: -</b> 
<p><u>Benefits</u>: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">(1) Reduced transport costs, exchange of ideas and sharing of natural resources.
<br>(2) Standard of living of rural population enhances.
<br>(3) More people get opportunities, which are not available in rural areas.
<br>(4) Social and religious taboos [prohibitions] / sanctions [laws] disappear.
<br>(5) Education.
<br>(6) Development.
<p><u>Limitations</u>: - 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">(1) Public health issues from air / water contamination.
<br>(2) Unemployment, under employment.
<br>(3) Severe shortage of housing.
<br>(4) Poverty, psychological problems, alcoholism, drugs, crime, other deviant behaviors.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.slideshare.net/saiyangoku/5effects-of-urbanization)

<p><b>Future trends and projections - Urbanization</b>: - 
<p>The Indian city dweller will have plenty more company - an additional 250 million people swelling the ranks of city population from an estimated 340 million in 2010 to 590 million in 2030. Cities will account for 70% of GDP [Gross Domestic Product] and will provide 85% of total tax revenues that will benefit the 200 million rural populations who live in proximity to 70 of the largest cities in the country.
<p>This report was published by MGI [McKinsey Global Institute] in April, 2010.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://urbanslate.wordpress.com/2010/06/02/473/)
